-- 01-research-plan-evolver-frames.cell
-- Execution trace of 01-research-plan-evolver.cell via eval-one
--
-- Problem: "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with
-- similar quality die?"

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 0: evaluate problem (trivial pass-through)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { problem } — only cell with all givens bound
-- Blocked: { hypothesize } — needs problem→statement
-- Blocked: everything else — transitive

⊢ problem
  given statement ≡ "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with similar quality die?"
  yield statement

-- eval-one: problem is a pass-through. statement is already bound via given ≡.
-- No ∴ body, no ⊢= body. Yield inherits from given.

  yield statement ≡ "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with similar quality die?"

-- oracle check:
--   ⊨ statement is a clear research question → ✓

-- state after frame 0: problem frozen.
-- Ready set: { hypothesize }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 1: evaluate hypothesize (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { hypothesize }
-- Blocked: { design-experiments } — needs hypothesize→hypotheses

⊢ hypothesize
  given problem→statement ≡ "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with similar quality die?"
  yield hypotheses[]

  ∴ Generate 3-5 distinct, testable hypotheses...

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield hypotheses ≡ [
    "H1: Projects with a single charismatic maintainer who actively engages contributors on social platforms attract exponentially more contributors than technically superior but socially quiet projects.",
    "H2: Projects that are adopted as dependencies by one or more popular frameworks experience a network-effect growth flywheel that sustains them independent of code quality.",
    "H3: Projects with low onboarding friction (good first-issue labels, CONTRIBUTING.md, quick build times) retain first-time contributors at 3-5x the rate of projects without these, and contributor retention is the primary predictor of survival.",
    "H4: Projects backed by corporate sponsors survive maintainer burnout because paid contributors bridge gaps; unfunded projects die when the primary maintainer exits regardless of community size."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(hypotheses) ≥ 3 → ✓ (4 hypotheses)
--   ⊨ each hypothesis proposes a testable causal claim → ✓
--     H1: charismatic maintainer → contributor growth (testable via social metrics)
--     H2: dependency adoption → growth flywheel (testable via package graph)
--     H3: onboarding friction → contributor retention (testable via issue labels, docs)
--     H4: corporate backing → burnout resilience (testable via funding data)
--   ⊨ hypotheses are mutually distinct → ✓ (social, ecosystem, onboarding, funding)

-- state after frame 1: hypothesize frozen.
-- Ready set: { design-experiments }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 2: evaluate design-experiments (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { design-experiments }
-- Blocked: { evaluate-feasibility } — needs design-experiments→experiments

⊢ design-experiments
  given hypothesize→hypotheses ≡ ["H1: Projects with a single charismatic...", "H2: Projects that are adopted...", "H3: Projects with low onboarding friction...", "H4: Projects backed by corporate sponsors..."]
  yield experiments[]

  ∴ For each hypothesis, design one experiment...

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield experiments ≡ [
    "E1 (tests H1): Sample 200 GitHub projects in the same domain (e.g., Python web frameworks) with similar star counts at year 1. Measure maintainer's Twitter/blog followers, GitHub comment responsiveness (median time to first reply), and conference talk count. Correlate with 5-year contributor growth rate. Outcome: if r > 0.5 between social engagement score and contributor growth, supports H1.",
    "E2 (tests H2): Using libraries.io dependency data, identify projects that were adopted by a top-50 npm/PyPI package between 2018-2020. Compare their contributor and download trajectories against matched controls (same language, similar stars, not adopted). Outcome: if adopted projects grow >2x faster, supports H2.",
    "E3 (tests H3): Scrape 500 GitHub repos for CONTRIBUTING.md presence, good-first-issue labels, and CI build time. Track first-time contributor return rate (contributed again within 6 months). Regression: does onboarding friction score predict return rate? Outcome: if friction explains >30% of variance in return rate, supports H3.",
    "E4 (tests H4): Identify 100 projects that lost their primary maintainer (no commits for 6+ months). Split by funding status (Open Collective, GitHub Sponsors, corporate employer). Compare survival rate (active 2 years later). Outcome: if funded projects survive at >2x the rate, supports H4."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(experiments) = length(hypotheses) → ✓ (4 = 4)
--   ⊨ each experiment maps to exactly one hypothesis → ✓ (E1→H1, E2→H2, E3→H3, E4→H4)
--   ⊨ each experiment specifies measurable outcomes → ✓ (all have quantitative thresholds)

-- state after frame 2: design-experiments frozen.
-- Ready set: { evaluate-feasibility }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 3: evaluate evaluate-feasibility (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { evaluate-feasibility }
-- Blocked: { spawn-experiments } — needs feasible[], hypotheses

⊢ evaluate-feasibility
  given design-experiments→experiments ≡ ["E1...", "E2...", "E3...", "E4..."]
  yield feasible[], infeasible[]

  ∴ Evaluate feasibility with publicly available data...

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield feasible ≡ [
    "E2 (tests H2): libraries.io provides full dependency graphs via API. npm/PyPI download stats are public. GitHub contributor counts are API-accessible. Fully feasible.",
    "E3 (tests H3): CONTRIBUTING.md and issue labels are GitHub API fields. CI build time is harder but approximable from Actions logs. First-time contributor detection is possible via commit history. Feasible with some approximation.",
    "E4 (tests H4): Open Collective and GitHub Sponsors data is partially public. Corporate employment is detectable from commit email domains. Maintainer departure detectable from commit gaps. Feasible with some manual validation."
  ]

  yield infeasible ≡ [
    "E1 (tests H1): Twitter follower counts require Twitter API (restricted since 2023). Conference talk data has no central registry. Blog presence requires manual search across platforms. INFEASIBLE — social media data access is unreliable and labor-intensive."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(feasible) + length(infeasible) = 4 → ✓ (3 + 1 = 4)
--   ⊨ each feasible experiment uses publicly available data sources → ✓
--     E2: libraries.io API, npm/PyPI, GitHub API
--     E3: GitHub API, Actions logs
--     E4: Open Collective, GitHub Sponsors, commit emails

-- state after frame 3: evaluate-feasibility frozen.
-- Ready set: { spawn-experiments }
-- NOTE: H1 is now orphaned — no experiment will test it.
--       The ⊢∘ loop should catch this and potentially revise or drop H1.

